<DOC><DOCNO> AP880729-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-88 2234EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-SAtlantic-Apartheid     07-29 0329</FIRST><SECOND>AM-SAtlantic-Apartheid,0339</SECOND><HEAD>South Atlantic Nations Condemn Apartheid, Shun Waste</HEAD><DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An unprecedented meeting of 22South Atlantic nations ended Friday with a call for sanctionsagainst South Africa and an end to transferring nuclear and toxicwaste to the region.   The participants also called on Argentina and Great Britain toreach a definitive peace settlement in their dispute over theFalkland Islands, off the Argentine coast.   Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and 19 African nations signed thedeclaration at the end of the five-day meeting, the first of itskind for the region.   The 22 countries met at Brazil's invitation to create a ``zoneof peace and cooperation'' in the South Atlantic. The conceptinvolves keeping the region free of military bases and nuclear armsin accordance with a 1986 U.N. resolution.   The countries voted to ``condemn the abhorrent policy of theracist regime of apartheid in South Africa, the continued illegaloccupation and colonial domination of Namibia, South African actsof aggression against Angola and other neighboring states.''   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregatedsociety in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote innational affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy andmaintain separate districts, schools and health services.   The 22 nations recognized SWAPO, the South West Africa People'sOrganization, as the ``sole and legitimate'' representative ofNamibia, also known as South-West Africa.   The group endorsed ``the imposition of comprehensive andmandatory sanctions against the South African regime.''   The statement also urged joint efforts to block transfer oftoxic waste to the South Atlantic. Countries in West Africa haverecently shown mounting concern over the dumping of garbage therefrom Western nations, including the United States.   The participants called on Argentina and Great Britain tocontinue talks on the future of the Falkland Islands, whichArgentina calls the Malvinas. Argentina claims it owns theBritish-held islands and waged an unsuccessful war in 1982 to takethem over.</TEXT></DOC>